Alembic — forward-only migrations.

Rule: every migration's `downgrade()` is implemented as

    raise NotImplementedError("downgrade is not supported")

Migrations move the schema forward. To undo one, write a new migration
that does whatever undoing is required, with `DROP` statements typed
into it by a human who has thought about which database they are
pointed at.

We had one production-data incident caused by a destructive command
running against the wrong cluster. The script that did it has been
removed; this rule closes off the other path that would let an
`alembic downgrade` do the same thing.

The `downgrade()` function still has to exist because Alembic expects
it. Make it raise; do not implement it.
